76561198025257956,Not Recommended,322920,15150120,"Posted: 31 March, 2015",all,RazgrizOne,"(sigh...) Lets be clear about this: I loved this game, I still do. But I cannot recommend this to anyone at all just because it is extremely unfinished. When the Pre-alpha started in December I had really high hopes for this game. But I quickly realized that a really buggy pre-alpha really hurt the publicity of this game, so much that I feared that this game would be scrapped. It seems as if my fears have come true.As a $30 dollar game it is alright. The objective of the game is to survive long enough so that you can gear up and hunt dinosaurs. It follows the basic structure of thehunter in that the OBJECTIVE is hunting. This confused allot of people at the beginning, they thought it was a DayZ with dino's which it is not. With a large Island and a 5 species of dinosaurs you can have alot of fun. Running from Raptors, hunting Triceratops, and teaming up to kill T-Rexes is essentially what you will be doing. Most of this game revolves around teamwork to take down the biggest and baddest of dinosaurs. This is really what made this game stand out. It fostered a teambuilding enviroment without holding your hand. But as with most pre-alpha's it had its downsides.It started with only 3 types of dinosaurs (which grew to 5 types) which really wasn't that great. The weapons were lacking, the AI was terrible and it was all around a buggy game. Over the past 3 months the developers had been working really hard to polish up the pre-alpha and so it seemed as if everything was going just fine. Alas that was not the case...Currently the game still feels like its stuck in pre-alpha, there are still bugs, a low amount of content, AI STILL SUCKS, there are only a few weapons in game, and in general it is unfinished all around. This really sucks as it had alot of potential to ge a GREAT game but in its current iteration I WOULD GIVE IT A 5/10 AT BEST.Will I still play it, Yeah. But I would not advise you to buy it. Hopefully the devs will continue to produce more content and this jewel of a game can be saved. If they do fix it I will revisit this revew but for now, save your money and buy any of the other great indie games out there. It will be a much better use of your time and money."
76561198029642831,Not Recommended,322920,27667583,"Posted: 26 November, 2016",all,Sleeper Agent of Planeptune,"A game that showed a lot of promise during the Early Access days and had the potential to become one of the best, most immersive and most realistic hunting simulators, in the end failed horribly to deliver. What we have now is a game with minimal content, barely acceptable for a ""full release"", while ridden with so many bugs and glitches that they alone could easily ruin the experience for many. In the end, it somehow managed to become a game that was much better and a lot more fun to play during its Early Access days and as long as the developing team refuses to care, fix problems and add new content, even as DLC, I personally wish it could revert to that.Positive:+ Large map, beautiful environment, realistic landscape+ Good atmosphere, ambient sounds, day-night cycle and weather effects+ The game gives a nice initial feeling and the first few times you get approached by a T-Rex can be pretty thrilling, but it gets old fast+ Controls when trying to aim are clunky, but that actually adds to the realism+ For a hunting simulator, I suppose it has a good variety of weaponsNegative:- The island may look beautiful at first, but once you've walked all over the map once, it all feels the same- Camouflage used to matter during Early Access, now it's irrelevant. Hiding prone and motionless under bushes saved your life more than often back then, now most of the time it makes no difference- Dinosaur AI, especially that of the T-Rex, has gotten worse and worse over the course of development. The T-Rex used to behave like a clueless animal when shot out of the blue, now it instantly locates your position and runs to you in a straight line, like a heat-seeking missile, stops and eats you without even wasting a second to look around for you. It doesn't get more unrealistic than that as in actuality, most of the time the animal wouldn't even be able to identify which direction it got wounded from- Only five species, two of which share the same model in different scales- All five species are aggressive, four of them being actual predators, the opposite of what you'd expect from a hunting session- On top of that, supplies and ammunition are so scarce that it feels a lot more like a survival game than a hunting game. Hence why I always called it ""theHunted: Primal"". The player is clearly the prey in this one- The dinosaurs never eat, drink, sleep or interact with each other, killing the realism- Hitboxes are and have always been a mess- Dinosaurs may still attack you through concrete walls and thick trees, one of the major glitches that was addressed countless times but was never fixed- Server issues and reports from players losing their entire inventories or never receiving the items purchased from the in-game after-death store are more frequent than one could imagineBorderline Ridiculous:... You can carry about 18 bullets for the .50 sniper rifle when you are in your underwear, but you can only carry about 15-16 if you put on pants and a shirt. Even less if you put on sunglasses and a hat!... The character runs out of stamina after sprinting for a few dozen meters, while the dinosaurs can sprint to the ends of eternity without pause... The character also has some sort of mental deficiency, as he/she suddenly becomes unable to throw a rock while crouching on one knee... Watching a T-Rex walking up an almost vertical hillside practically defies descriptionConclusion:Bugs, glitches and lack of content aside, it may be worth the purchase for its current price of €10 if you don't expect to be amazed, if you are curious and if you don't mind the expense and the indifference of the creators, as it will probably offer some good times, but let me remind you that the game cost €20 during Early Access. That alone says a lot."
