76561198113976076,Not Recommended,322920,15195131,"Posted: 3 April, 2015",all,patrick.mcenaney,"Let me start by saying that theHunter: Primal has a lot of potential to be a great game.I'm a huge fan of the original ""theHunter"", and have been playing it for at least 5 years now. Still play it quite often to this day.I was always a fan of hunting games (Deer Hunter 2005, was amazing), and dinosaur games (Many hours were spent playing the Carnivores series of games, even the broken JP: Trespasser and Turok), so when I heard about theHunter:Primal, I was stoked to say the least.Before purchasing this game I had high hopes of it basically being a clone of the original game, replacing the local fauna from our time period with the prehistoric variety, while keeping the same solid, fun gameplay that has made theHunter so popular since it's release quite a few years ago.What I got feels like an extremely rushed, unfinished, buggy ""game"" that still feels like it's in an early alpha state.I can't stress this enough: THIS GAME DOES NOT FEEL FINISHED.The animations are for the most part awful. Don't get me wrong; when the dinosaurs aren't walking or anything they look very nice, and as realistic as anyone could expect from species that have been extinct for millions of years. But as soon as they start to walk/run, that's where the animations all go to hell. I've seen triceratops doing backflips trying to walk up hills, Dissappearing right infront of your eyes, and then magically reappearing a few hunded feet away.I've had Tyrannosaurs walk right up to me and stumble around me in circles before walking away, and when they get 100 feet or so away from me, suddenly realize I'm there, and then eat me (I was walking around while standing up this entire time).I've 1-hit-killed a Utah Raptor with a makeshift bow, while I was unable to drop a Triceratops by putting 6x 12guage slugs into it point blank, among others.Another problem I have with this ""game"" is where in the original, you would spot lots of animal tracks, etc. Making it fun to stalk whichever animal you were following. In Primal, any sort of tracks or sign seem to be very few, and far between. I've followed a Triceratops as it stomps through the river banks for about 20 minutes, all while not leaving a single track. How are you supposed to hunt in this ""hunting game"" if there are no tracks or sign to go by?Also, why did they feel the need to make this a survival style game, where you spend most of your time wandering around aimlessly trying to find a weapon powerful enough to even kill a raptor the size of a turkey?I'd be much happier if they went with the same hunting mechanic as the original where you pick your weapon loadout at the lodge before you head out.  I know they basically replaced the lodge with the drop ships, but the fact that you need to earn so many credits for even a basic weapon, makes this game ridiculously tedious, and hard to enjoy.You should start the game with at least a capable rifle, and then scavenge/buy more ammo as you need it. Sure, have the player able to find new weapons in crates still, but at least give them a capable weapon to start with so they can enjoy the game. I didn't buy a hunting game to ""survive"", I bought it so I could hunt dinosaurs. And if I were going to hunt dinosaurs in real life, you can be damn sure I'd be taking a rifle with me from the get-go.Another small issue that needs to be fixed is the weird ""wave-splashing"" effect, that seems to come out of the ground or in the middle of a lake. I think the water would look much better if that effect was just scrapped completely.The flora in this game also doesn't seem to be nearly as convincing as it is in the original theHunter game. I'm not sure what it is about it, but it just doesn't look as good as the original. I love the look of the forests in the original game. The jungles in Primal, not so much.Also, the sound is a big issue with me. In the original ""theHunter"", the sound has it's issues, sure (mainly just the fact that footsteps would sound like they're on top of you, even though they could be 100 yards away), but for the most part. ""theHunter"" sounds beautiful, the entire time you're playing.In Primal, the sounds in the forests/jungle aren't anywhere near as immersive, and it also suffers from the same ""close-sounding"" footsteps problem. Also, some of the sounds are just strange. I'm not sure if it's just Utah Raptors, or all (I think there's like five...) of the species, but there's always this strange ""dragging"" sound when one is close, and I have no idea what that sound is supposed to represent, but it just sounds awful, and not natural at all.I've also encountered quite a few areas where there is a beeping sound as if I'm close to a supply crate, but there is nothing to be found. So after searching the area for a while to see if there is a ""hidden"" crate, I just give up, and leave. This has happened in quite a few areas for me.Now, I don't want to sound like I'm completely bashing this game, because I really want it to succed. I just feel that there's no way they should have let it out of early access in the current state it's in, and they definitely shouldn't have called it a full release. It's not even in beta state in my opinion. They should have spent at least another 6-8 months on it, and ironed out the bugs at least, before releasing it. And that's not including all of the gameplay issues I have with this game.I wouldn't recommend buying this game yet, wait for them to (hopefully) release some major patches for it, to bring it closer to something that feels like an actual game, and not a tech demo. I'm glad they didn't go with the subscription price model like the original (Although I'm guessing that's the only thing that's kept the project alive for so long, otherwise they'd have no incentive to keep updating it), but I fear this ""game"" is going to become filled with microtransactions to bring it up to the caliber of hunting simulation it's predecessor is."
