,Recommended,322920,16068552,"Posted: 29 May, 2015",all,Apsalar,"EDIT(Sept14th2015): This review was made with high hopes, but the devs have since moved their focus to other projects, and much of my happy vision will never be realized. Nonetheless, it's a good game and it's actively maintained at the moment.First off, let me clarify: this is NOT a survival game. As long as you don't walk off a cliff or get torn limb from limb by a dinosaur, you'll live forever.So then what is it? Well I have seen two ways of playing this game.  You can play it as an exploration game, full of emergent narratives and fantastic vistas waiting to be seen by those willing to tread the most dangerous paths. Or, you can play it as a hunting game, full of big things to kill with your big gun and get money and a fancy dead trophy.  I am aware that the game is being designed with the latter in mind. But emergence is one of the truly wondrous elements of the video game as a narrative medium.  New and unanticipated things happen when your audience is also your performer and your performance.You have probably guessed by now which play style I embrace.  I have ZERO interest in game hunting, dinosaur or otherwise.  I am, however, interested in walking among dinosaurs, as I have dreamed of fondly ever since that childhood  trans-Atlantic flight I spent reading a National Geographic book about them cover to cover, and I apparently was so adorably excited about the whole thing that the pilot gave me his Lufthansa captain's pin and patted me on the head.  More so than any other game I've played, this game allows me to do that.Dinosaurs and man, two species separated by 65 million years of evolution have just been suddenly thrown back into the mix together. How can we possibly have the slightest idea what to expect? -Dr Alan GrantLuckily you have me to tell you a little bit about what to expect. The very limpid premise to justify your simultaneous existence with dinosaurs is that you are a scout selected to spearhead a colonization effort on this alien ""Eden.""  Isn't it a little chilling that we are presumably doing this by enacting the mass slaughter of the native fauna? There's some commentary there, intended or otherwise.Like I said at the beginning, this is not a survival game.  There are no hunger or thirst mechanics.  There's a fairly typical stamina bar depleted by sprinting or melee but quickly recharged.  There is food out there in the wilds to be scavenged, but despite its realistic appearance it's arcade food: eat it to restore health.  Scavenging rather than crafting is your main way of acquiring weapons and equipment.  There are busted colony pods, half-finished bunkers, and the well-supplied bodies of many a less fortunate colonist scattered throughout the landscape.  Early on this will be your only source of gear that *might* protect you when you accidentally cross upwind of that T-Rex you've been tracking.  But more likely you will join the broken bodies of the brave stacked up for carrion (to paraphrase Homer).Playing as an explorer is indeed punctuated by intense action.  I will shoot a dinosaur to save myself. I will flail my gun around in terror as I hear but can't see the pack of utahraptors close in on me. I will use my machete to hack aside the velociraptor lunging my jugular.  When you kill and catalog a dinosaur you get money and experience based on its rarity, its difficulty to kill, and the integrity of the corpse (prohint: you won't get much for blasting a campysaur with you shotty).  Every time you perish you are brought to a shop screen where you can purchase gear.  The availability of different items is a function of both your xp level and your accumulated capital.  Slowly but surely you get to a point where you can survive most run-ins with smaller dinosaurs on your own.  If you plan to take on a T-Rex or if you want to blast a herd of peaceful triceratops for no reason, hop on a multiplayer server and team up.  Your character is persistent across servers, but taking down a Tyrannosaur (possibly to protect those innocent triceratops) requires well coordinated tactical engagement. Still most of you will die. It's glorious.I continue to thoroughly enjoy this game.  The crass masculinity infecting the multiplayer chat can be irritating, but it's not game-ruining, and frankly when is it not asserting itself with knuckles dragged and chests bumped in whatever multiplayer chat you find.  The graphics are beautiful, gameplay is challenging and the shooting mechanics are fairly realistic.  The dino AI gets better with every update.  They really will sniff you out if your upwind and enact coordinated assaults complete with feints to draw your attention while they flank.  It's wondrous.If you are now or ever were a dinosaur nerd, this game is essential.  Highly recommended."
