76561197968809599,Recommended,322920,13470903,"Posted: 20 December, 2014",all,Chazmeister,"If you've played The Hunter (no I'm not going to type it like this: theHunter), then this is basically The Hunter but with dinosaurs, and if the idea of that floats your boat, then by all means give it a go.If you've not played The Hunter before, then basically it's a hunting sim with dinosaurs. You get a large tropical volcanic hawaiian style island to roam and explore at your lesuire which looks fantastic. As with The Hunter they've done a great job on making the environment feel very natural and believable. Fancy a quick break somewhere nice in the sun? Then go for a hike around this island. Of course you won't be able to completely relax because the place is also inhabited by dinosaurs, which you can either try and avoid or hunt down. The current premise behind all this is that you're a prisoner/pioneer in the future who has been dumped on this planet and tasked with clearing it of dinosaurs. Evidence of previous pioneers is still littered and dotted around the landscape in places.To aid you in hunting you get a sort of hunters mate. A little electronic PDA style device that you can use to scan foot prints or scat or even dinosaur calls to help give you a idea of their directional location. It's not always 100% on the ball so you have to use a bit of your own judgment as well. By default, evidence of dino tracks are highlighted with glowing red markers making them much easier to spot in amongst all the thick vegitation. You can turn these markers off and rely only on your own abilities to spot the foot prints and mounds of dino poo. Trust me, even without the glowing markers, trying to spot even a 3 foot mound of poo is tricky, let alone a foot print in the grass. The PDA however will still chirp up and notify you when you do stumble over some evidence of dino tracks.So what weapons and gear do you get to hunt down these dinos? Well it's an odd assortment considering it's set in the future and that you have been specifially tasked with hunting down dinosaurs. You'd think they'd give you a suit of armour and a gun that could knock down an elephant, but instead you start dressed in a t-shirt next to a pod that contains a bow and a tiny clutch of arrows. Yes, they gave you bows and arrows to take down dinosaurs. I guess the folks in charge back on earth must have been reading the Turok comics in order to formulate their dino eradication strategy. As you move around the landscape, you will come across crates with other weapons, items of clothing and medi kits. Mostly you will find more arrows and bows, but there are also shotguns, pistols and rifles to be found. Annoyingly you won't always find the ammo with the gun, meaning you will have to decide whether to haul around a dead weight with you in the hope of finding some ammo for it. All items affect your overall weight, which in turn affects your movement speed and how long you can sprint for. Clothing items currently seem to offer no bonuses, it's just fancy dress right now. Another issue is that items will not stack at the moment either. So if you have 5 arrows and you pick up another 3, they will stay as two separate amounts in your inventory. Fortunately inventory space is not a problem right now anyway as there is almost no way you could fill it with the current weight limitations. However when you equip the 3 arrows it won't automatically then use up the bunch of 5 after you've used the bunch of 3. You will have to then equip that bunch of 5 manually too. All simple issues that will get sorted in time I'm sure.The weapons themselves for the most part handle well. The bow is a bit of a pain, as you need to aim it before charging it for firing and you can't do it in quick succession. Meaning if 3 raptors get on your trail and all you have is a bow, then you're dead meat. You might take one, but the other two will get you for sure. A shotgun fully loaded with slugs will even up the score some what. As with The Hunter all the beasties take location damage to things like heart and lungs etc and even if they do a runner they can still bleed out and die later. If like me you have no idea of the internal anatomy of dinosaurs, then taking them down with shots to the vitals will be more about luck and guess work. Currently there are only 3 dinosaur types in the game, the Triceratops, Utahraptors and the T-Rex. The dinos are not omnipotent and you can generally sneak up on them with reasonable ease if you stay low and stick to cover. They can of course also sneak up on you. A few times as I've been strolling along I heard a rustle from behind me and turned around to see a raptor sneaking up on me. If you see 3 snooping around behind you trying to pick up on your trail, then get worried. Avoid the T-Rex. Triceratops is a herbivore and is the best one to actively hunt down yourself without worrying that it's going to eat you instead.I haven't tried playing it with other folks yet, only ""singleplayer"", so I can't tell you how good the network code is etc. To play, you have to create a game and set the usual things like how many other players you want to be able to join in and give your game a password. So currently to play it single player just set the players to 1 and password it. In the 3 hours I played last night, I did not encounter any major show stopping bugs or crashes. It all seemed pretty stable to me. Playing it on an i5 with 8 Gb of ram and a GTX770, all on max settings and it all runs just fine.Right now the game is a bit content thin as previously noted. Only 1 island, 3 dinos, a small smattering of weapons and not a lot else. However of course I expect that to change as the game is delveloped. What is currently there though, is in a very playable state, and if hunting and exploring are your thing then this should provide you with a good few hours of enjoyment even at this stage. The Hunter is currently the best hunting game out there (shame about the microtransactions), so this game already has a good foundation in that respect. It's more or less really just going to be a case of waiting for them to develop the content with this one.What would I like to see going forwards? More islands with different biomes like windswept deserts and dunes, arctic areas, temperate woodlands and plains. More dinosaurs of course and interactivity beween the different dinosaurs, as I haven't really seen any evidence of that yet. More kit and perhaps a bit of minor base building maybe. All stuff that I'm pretty sure we'll see eventually anyway."
