76561198075610928,Recommended,322920,17636393,"Posted: 20 August, 2015",all,wboler05,"I'm pretty torn on this game.  You're thrown into a new world through an escape pod and left with a machete and a map chip to help guide you through an expansive world.  Your apparent objective is to hunt down as many dinosaurs before succumbing to your inevitable demise.  Once you die, your equipment and your body is left to be eaten while a ""family member"" is spawned at a random place nearby.  If you want that equipment back, you basically have to trek through the jungles and mountains to regain your possessions or search for more boxes of goodies scattered throughout the lands.The pros of this game are that you get to walk around with dinosaurs, enjoying the view, and taking the time to learn the long-lost art of tracking down game.  You can spend hours doing this.The cons are plentiful.  There aren't many dinosaurs.  You'll only get the 5 types of dinosaurs advertised.  It can get pretty repetitive hunting down the same dinosaurs over and over.  There's not much variety in that sense.  To make matters worse, the AI for the dinosaurs are pretty bad.  They each have their own way to move, which of course makes sense, but they tend to move directly towards a waypoint.  If you run out of the way, they will not change their path.  They'll arive at the waypoint, then turn around to recalculate.  This doesn't make the game any easier, because the T-Rex will kill you, but the realism takes a hit in that sense.To add to the cons, the game is not fun when you're playing it alone.  It's all fine and dandy while learning how to do things, but once you figure out the main aspect of the game it gets pretty boring.  I can only play long enough until I die, and then I shut the game off.There are no missions or no primary objectives.  You just kill dinosaurs and hope to harvest them for points.  You collect the same objects over and over, and then go out and use them against only a few of the dinosaurs.  The rest of the time, you're tracking for hours looking for the one that you wounded while avoiding the ones that are just too hard to kill or more likely to kill you in one blow.  You need multiplayer to make this game enjoyable.And my biggest buzz kill is no controller support.  I never liked keyboard/mouse games, especially when I have a perfectly good controller that can execute all of the small list of tasks available to the player.  Your guy can't even climb, jump, or swim, so there's nothing complex behind slapping on a few instructions for a controller.Overall, I say it's a well made game that I enjoyed for some time and would recommend for others to play, but like the dinosaurs it doesn't stand the test of time."
