76561198272239061,Recommended,322920,28129710,"Posted: 1 December, 2016",all,Argagax,"A pretty simple, ""small"" game, as it's only one map (vastly larger than any of the hunting reserves in theHunter though), with only five species of animals, only one of which is a herbivore.I haven't played many survival games but I imagine there being more focus on not dying due to thirst, starvation or exposure in those - since this is still ""theHunter"", the only thing that can kill you here is either the animals, or your own stupidity (don't walk into deep water or jump off mountains, is my advise. Also - the flowers hate you).It's a slow and thus relaxing game, where most of the time you are just walking from base to base, trying to upgrade your gear and weapons, while you also have to be constantly on the alert from any suspicious sights or sounds. Many times have I been taken by a hungry rex or pack of utahraptors when not paying enough attention.I previously gave this a negative review because of the way the devs treated the problems players (paying buyers) had - but since they fixed it to the best of their ability, I'm changing it to what I really think of the game.I've played it on and off for almost 1½ year, and keep coming back to it. In some ways, I actually like it more than theHunter, as it's more sport when you risk dying, instead of just scaring your prey off (and of course, the waaay lower price, and I thought the ""ethical"" weapons in theHunter became too restrictive as they kept changing the rules).There is not really anything to do or any missions to complete, which I wish the devs could introduce (as well as more species!), but the Steam accomplishments keep me motivated, as well as making up my own goals. Finding a ""rare"" dino (mutation) is really something, and I still haven't caught my queen rex."
